<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="198" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1129,1406]" pageId="1" pageNumber="198">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,373,1129,1154]" pageId="1" pageNumber="198">Generic diagnosis.</emphasis>
Prostomium with middle lobe surrounded by inflated lobe, lacking glandular ridges. Buccal tentacles smooth. Two to four pairs of cirriform branchiae. Segment II usually without chaetae, or exceptionally with minute chaetae. Thorax with 11–14 uncinigers. Modified or intermediate segments absent. Abdomen with rudimentary notopodia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="198" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1129,1406]" pageId="1" pageNumber="198">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1273,1298]" pageId="1" pageNumber="198">Remarks.</emphasis>
With the description of new 
<taxonomicName box="[682,760,1274,1297]" class="Polychaeta" family="Ampharetidae" genus="Amage" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="1" pageNumber="198" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[682,760,1274,1297]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="198">Amage</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with unusual features (
<bibRefCitation author="Schuller" box="[1143,1431,1273,1298]" pageId="1" pageNumber="198" refString="Schuller, M. &amp; Jirkov, I. A. (2013) New Ampharetidae (Polychaeta) from the deep Southern Ocean and shallow Patagonian waters. Zootaxa, 3692 (1), 204 - 237. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3692.1.11" type="journal article" year="2013">Schüller &amp; Jirkov 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Reuscher" box="[151,382,1309,1334]" pageId="1" pageNumber="198" refString="Reuscher, M., Fiege, D. &amp; Imajima, M. (2015) Ampharetidae (Annelida: Polychaeta) from Japan. Part IV. Miscellaneous genera. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 95 (6), 1105 - 1125. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / S 0025315415000545" type="journal article" year="2015">
Reuscher 
<emphasis box="[262,318,1309,1333]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="198">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
) and the proposed synonymy of 
<taxonomicName box="[748,826,1310,1333]" class="Polychaeta" family="Ampharetidae" genus="Amage" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="1" pageNumber="198" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[748,826,1310,1333]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="198">Amage</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with other genera (
<bibRefCitation author="Jirkov" box="[1043,1181,1309,1334]" pageId="1" pageNumber="198" refString="Jirkov, I. A. (2011) Discussion of taxonomic characters and classification of Ampharetidae (Polychaeta). Italian Journal of Zoology, 78, 78 - 94. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 11250003.2011.617216" type="journal article" year="2011">Jirkov 2011</bibRefCitation>
), the generic diagnosis has become quite inclusive. A revision of 
<taxonomicName box="[624,702,1346,1369]" class="Polychaeta" family="Ampharetidae" genus="Amage" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="1" pageNumber="198" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[624,702,1346,1369]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="198">Amage</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is urgently needed to determine if this is justified, or if the genus needs to be split.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
